¹ ¹ Thereupon he said.‘ But of course he could only say what is here put into his mouth, if the demands made seemed to him just, and the war therefore unavoidable.

² ‘ The war was agreed to.' Bellum erat consensum is an unusual expression used here by Livy, in all probability. merely because he was quoting from some old document. The ordinary construction would have been consensum erat de bello, or consensum decretum erat de bello. The expression samatus consensit bellum, in Livy, viii. 6, must also be considered as a quotation from an ancient formula, for properly consentire is not transitive. In this passage some editions read bellum erac consensu, contrary, however, to the authority of the best manuscripts.
